# Styling the Body and Root Element

There are several ways to style the main page/root element:

## 1. **CSS File (Recommended)**

Create a `styles.css` file and target the elements directly:

```css
/* Style the body */
body {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

/* Style the root div */
#root {
  display: flex;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

Then link it in your HTML `<head>`:
```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
```

## 2. **Inline Styles in HTML**

```html
<body style="margin: 0; padding: 0; background-color: #f0f0f0;">
  <div id="root" style="display: flex; min-height: 100vh;"></div>
</body>
```

## 3. **Stylesheet in HTML Head**

```html
<head>
  <style>
    body {
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      background-color: #f0f0f0;
    }
    #root {
      min-height: 100vh;
    }
  </style>
</head>
```

## 4. **JavaScript (if using a framework)**

```javascript
document.body.style.backgroundColor = '#f0f0f0';
document.getElementById('root').style.minHeight = '100vh';
```

## Common Reset Pattern

Most modern apps start with a reset to remove default margins:

```css
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

body {
  font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', sans-serif;
}

#root {
  width: 100%;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

**Best practice:** Use a dedicated CSS file with a reset stylesheet for maintainability.

